results.snippet: At the center of Moscow's building boom is a 33-year-old adventure-seeking multimillionaire with a pet boa constrictor.
results.lead_paragraph: Sergei Polonsky was short 900 tons of concrete, and he wasn't interested in excuses. It was a sweaty July morning at a construction site just outside central Moscow, and several contractors were arguing over whom to blame. The air-conditioned office overlooked hard-hatted workers scrambling through the dust several stories below, cranes swinging into position high above their heads.

results.abstract: Space shuttle Atlantis circles International Space Station to check for damage from orbital debris (S)

headline.main: Shuttle Separates From Station And Prepares for Return to Earth

results.snippet: Astronauts aboard the space shuttle Atlantis performed a fly-around to get a look at the International Space Station before leaving.
results.lead_paragraph: Astronauts aboard the space shuttle Atlantis said goodbye Sunday morning to their hosts at the International Space Station, separated the two craft and performed a fly-around to get a 360-degree look at the station to check for damage from orbital debris. The video from space showed the station gleaming against the black backdrop of the void, and then the Earth, and then space again as the shuttle looped around it. The new solar arrays delivered by the shuttle and installed by the crew extended from one side.

results.abstract: Crew on International Space Station repairs oxygen generation unit that overheated and emitted strong odor; crew also reports to NASA that there is spill of clear fluid that could be potassium hydroxide, caustic chemical used in unit; NASA declares brief emergency; drawing; photo (M)

headline.main: Overheated Device Leads to Brief Space Station Emergency

results.snippet: The three-man crew aboard the International Space Station scrambled to deal with an overheated oxygen generator and a possible chemical spill.
results.lead_paragraph: The three-man crew aboard the International Space Station scrambled yesterday morning to deal with an overheated oxygen generator and a possible chemical spill that caused NASA briefly to declare a station emergency. ''Smoke in the cabin was what we thought we were dealing with originally,'' said Michael T. Suffredini, the head of the station program, in a morning news briefing in Houston. The nature of the problem proved to be more slippery, but the astronauts -- Pavel V. Vinogradov of Russia, Col. Jeffrey N. Williams of the Army and Thomas Reiter of Germany -- ''did a great job'' of reacting quickly, Mr. Suffredini said.
